6)NOT_SUPPOSRTED:
  -> If a current transaction exists, first suspends it, and then the business logic is executed
     without a transaction.

7)SUPPORTED:
  ->If a transaction exists it will run it with, if no second transaction it will run without transaction


  Propagation 	   If Active Transaction Exists	              If No Transaction Exists
  REQUIRED	        Joins current	                            Creates new
  REQUIRES_NEW	    Suspends current; creates new	            Creates new
  NESTED	        Creates savepoint (nested)	                Creates new
  SUPPORTS	        Joins current	                            Runs non-transactionally
  NOT_SUPPORTED	    Suspends current; runs non-tx	            Runs non-transactionally
  MANDATORY	        Joins current	                            Throws Exception
  NEVER	            Throws Exception	                        Runs non-transactionally


Isolation levels in Transactional:
->Transaction isolation defines how data integrity is maintained when multiple transactions occur concurrently

Types:
->DEFAULT
->READ_UNCOMMITTED
->READ_COMMITTED
->REPEATABLE_READ
->SERIALIZABLE

1)DEFAULT :
 -> Uses the default isolation level of the underlying database.
   Ex: PostgreSQL, Oracle, SQL Server: Typically READ_COMMITTED.
   Ex: MySQL (InnoDB): Typically REPEATABLE_READ

2)READ_UNCOMMITTED:
  ->The lowest level. Allows a transaction to read data that has been modified but not yet committed by another
     transaction (known as a dirty read). It provides the highest performance but lowest consistency

3)READ_COMMITTED :
  ->Prevents dirty reads by ensuring a transaction can only read data that has already been committed. However,
     non-repeatable reads and phantom reads can still occur.

4)REPEATABLE_READ :
  -> Ensures that if you read the same row twice within a transaction, you get the same result even if other
     transactions have committed changes to it. It prevents dirty and non-repeatable reads but still allows phantom
     reads (new rows appearing in a range query).

5)SERIALIZABLE :
  -> The highest and most restrictive level. It executes transactions as if they were sequential, preventing all
     anomalies (dirty reads, non-repeatable reads, and phantom reads). This can significantly impact performance due
     to heavy locking


Note :
Dirty Read:
  -> Reading data from another transaction that hasn't been committed yet; if that transaction rolls back, your
     data becomes invalid.
Non-repeatable Read	:
  -> Reading the same row twice and getting different values because another transaction updated and committed it
     in between.
Phantom Read :
  -> Re-running a range query and getting a different number of rows because another transaction inserted or
     deleted records.






